(698, 'event', '68', 'comment', 'EN', '  When France fell in June 1940 there were many French civilians and military personnel in the United Kingdom, including those returning from missions in Norway.  Most of these chose to return to occupied or Vichy France whilst a small  number remained in Britain with the intention of contributing to the liberation of their homeland.\r\n\r\nVery quickly their numbers were reinforced by a steady flow of evadees from occupied france, often via Spanish prisons, or by small boat from Britanny.  Many were responding to the call of General de Gaulle to continue the fight for freedom from Britain.\r\n\r\n\r\n', '*', '2003-03-24 13:30:28'),
(699, 'event', '69', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>In July 1941 De Gaulle was eager,despite its small size, that the Free French should participate fully and would take paret in the fighting in the Near-East.  As well the wish to show Free France playing an active role in the war there was also a desire to ensure that as ex French territories became liberated they did not become annexed by Britain.  To this end he asked for the 1 C.P. to be moved out to Lebanon.  At this time, Syria and Lebanon had just been liberated by the Allies. Most of the 1st CIA were sent to Glasgow where they joined the troop ship Cameronia on 21st July.  After a long sea voyage around the Cape with a change of ship at Durban, the company eventuaty arrive at Beiruit in September after two months at sea.</p>', 'David Portier', '2013-12-15 14:24:20'),
(700, 'event', '69', 'comment', 'FR', '<p >Juillet 1941, le général de Gaulle tient particulièrement, malgré son petit nombre, à ce que la France Libre soit présente partout et participe aux combats du Proche-Orient. Il souhaite ainsi faire la preuve que la France Libre occupe un rôle actif dans la conduite de la guerre et également s\'assurer que les territoires français libérés ne seront pas alors dirigés par les Britanniques. Dans ce but, il réclame donc que la 1re CP soit envoyée au Levant. A cette date, la Syrie et le Liban viennent d\'être libéré par les Alliés.</p><p ><br></p><p >Le 21 juillet 1941, la majorité des éléments de la 1re CP embarquent à Greenock à bord du transport de troupes S/S Cameronia. Le convoi prend la mer le 3 août et atteint Freetown le 17 puis Capetown le 2 septembre. Le 5 septembre, les hommes font escale à Durban puis embarquent sur le S/S New Amsterdam. Le convoi CM 18 atteint Suez le 18 septembre.</p><p >A la suite d\'un long périple, la Compagnie atteint enfin Beyrouth le 23 septembre après deux mois en mer.</p>', 'David P', '2019-09-26 11:55:39'),
(701, 'event', '70', 'comment', 'EN', 'Following the request for an Armistice made by maréchal Pétain the previous day, général de Gaulle made an appeal over the BBC to the French people. He asked them to join him in England to continue the fight for freedom.', '*', '2003-04-06 09:12:43'),
(702, 'event', '71', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>After parachute training, the 1 C.I.A was installed at Exbury in the training camp at Inchmery House, situate on the coast facing the Isle of Wight. The company was then renamed 1ère Compagnie Parachutiste and then included 10 officers, 12 NCOs and 74 men. There the parachutists received an advanced and physically demanding commando training.<br />Two distinct groups were set up. The first received combat training including training in unarmed combat. The second was destined for undercover work and espionage.<br />At the end of June, Général de Gaulle ordered the 1st CP to Syria. Capitaine Bergé left behind at Inchmery the undercover specialist. On the 16th July, the rest of the unit arrived at London and spent several days in a transit camp at Barnes.</p>\r\n<p>List of French parachutists known to be present at Exbury in may 1941 :</p>', 'David Portier', '2017-07-29 10:43:06'),
(703, 'event', '72', 'comment', 'EN', ' The target of the second mission was to destroy a power station at Pressac supplying a submarine base near Bordeaux.  Le Tac was to join the stick when they were dropped in France on the night of the 11th May.   The operation, supported by a group of resistance who had been set up by Berge during the Savanah operation, when he took time to visit his family home near Bordeaux, was a success and the power station was destroyed.  The stick returned to the UK via Spain in July 1941.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(704, 'event', '73', 'comment', 'EN', ' The 1CIA arrived in the Levant on 23th September 1941.  The Syrian war was over and the bulk of the Army of the Levant had returned to occupied France.  There were however many Free French from the Colonial troups who were waiting to join the emerging Free French Forces.  As the main encounters with the enemy were currently in North Africa there was no plans to move these forces to other theatres of war.  There were airforce squadrons, Foreign Legion battalions and other land forces groups recruiting and training in the region.   \r\n\r\nBerge was activily trying to recruit into his young Company, as well as to find training facilities and, of course, a mission to enable them to engage with the enemy.   Training facilities for parachuting were non existent,  learning to roll off moving lorries was one improvisation.  During this period there were losses from parachute and explosives training.  Gaultier died on Christmas eve as a result of an acident with explosives.\r\n\r\nThe Company was based at Meze the airfield of Damascus.\r\n\r\nEventually the french forces were authorised to colaborate with British forces and a consolidation took place with many soldiers moving from the Levant to Egypt.   Berge obtained pernission to integrate his company with the SAS battalion being formed by Stirling at Kabret on the Suex canal.', '*', '2003-04-10 04:54:05'),
(705, 'event', '74', 'comment', 'EN', 'On Christmas eve 1941 Gaultier was killed during an explosives training session.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(706, 'event', '75', 'comment', 'EN', 'Three of the company were killed during a training flight together with the pilot Newman.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(707, 'event', '76', 'comment', 'EN', 'General de Gaulle supported by Churchill, became the beacon for those who refused to accept defeat.  The HQ of the Free French was established at St Stephens House in London, this was the destination for those French men and women arriving at London who wanted to continue the fight.  \r\n\r\nAmong these was Capitain George Berge.  Wounded during the defence of France he was recovering in hospital when he learned of the armistice. The 19th of June, he succeeded in boarding a boat at St_Jean de Luz and arrived in Great Brittain the 23rd of June.  The next day he reported for duty to Stephen House. Having briefy been a member of a parachute company in 1937, he saw the value of parachutists in the eventual liberation of France and lobbied de Gaulle for permission to create a parachute company.  On 15 September 1940 the 1ère Compagnie de l\'Infanterie de l\'Air was established with Bergé in command.', '*', '2003-04-06 09:29:46'),
(708, 'event', '77', 'comment', 'EN', 'When the the 1st CIA left for the Near-East, a small number of men under the command of capitaine René Weill Ã‚Â« Georges Ã‚Â» remained in England aand were transfered to the  Old Dean Camp near Camberley.  Some were posted to the B.C.R.A, the French intelligence services or worked with the British Special Operations Executive (SOE). In May capitaine Weill was sent on a mission in France.  Capitaine Coulet then commanded the Infanterie de l\'Air at Camberley until December 1942.  Little by little, new voluntiers managed to reach Britain and enlisted in the Free French parachiutists.', 'david', '2008-03-10 19:49:01'),
(709, 'event', '78', 'comment', 'EN', 'The first mission after training of the 1 CIA was to be dropped into Britanny near Vannes.  The intention was to attack a bus carrying German aircrew who were harrassing Allied shipping in the Channel.  Unfortunately the crews were relocated to the base and the daily trip no longer took place.  Berge and Forman returned by submarine on the 5th April. Le Tac remaining in France.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(710, 'event', '79', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>The French SAS (1BIA) paraded in London on Bastille day 1943. The banner was carried by Victor Itturia flanked by Jean Le Gall and Jean Roquemaure.</p>', 'paul golder', '2013-12-02 10:21:32'),
(711, 'event', '86', 'comment', 'EN', 'In May 1944 the SAS battalions were transported by train from Scotland  to Fairford in Gloucestershire.  This became the secret airfield from which they were to be flown into France whan the invasion was launched.  All leave was cancelled and final preparations commenced.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(712, 'event', '87', 'comment', 'EN', 'After a year in the Middle east and North Africa, at the end of march 1943, the group under S/Lt Martin also arrived having finished the war in North Africa.  They arrived at Liverpool before the main returners who were sailing around the cape.', '*', '2003-05-25 10:09:29'),
(713, 'event', '88', 'comment', 'EN', 'To be recognised Free French you had to have signed an engagement before the 1st August 1943.', 'David Portier', '2005-12-18 06:03:13'),
(714, 'event', '89', 'comment', 'EN', 'The French SAS batalions had important roles assigned to them in support of the invasion.   In Traditional SAS fashion they were to be dropped behind enemy lines and through sabotage, ambush and organising the internal resistance disrupt and distract the occupying forces from reaching the Normandy front.  Then they were to faciliate the advance of the main liberation forces.  Being lightly armed they were not in a position to engage in the sort of fixed battles that the invasion force was fighting.  4SAS was dropped in force into Britanny, whilst 3SAS followed and was launched on a number of missions across the middle of France.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(715, 'event', '90', 'comment', 'EN', 'As the war in France drew to a close the SAS were gathered at bases in the Champagne at Montmirail and Eperney. In free Paris on Armistice day 1944 the SAS paraded down the Champs Elysees. They were led by Lt/Col Bourgoin with Lt Legrand carrying the SAS flag. In front of the Arc de Triomphe General De Gaulle presented the 2nd RCP (4SAS) with the Croix de Compagnon de la Liberation. This was the first time that the regiment as a whole had worn the red beret. Following the end of action in France a certain amount of change hit the SAS. Many of the senior officers including Bourgoin were given other responsibiliteis and Puech Samson took command of the 4 SAS and Conan the 3rd.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(716, 'event', '91', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>From the 15th of June 3SAS started to arrive in France.  From the west coast to Lyon and the Rhone valley all the main arteries which the enemy might use to retreat or consolidate were the target of SAS activity.</p>', 'paul golder', '2012-09-19 03:02:58'),
(717, 'event', '92', 'comment', 'EN', 'The intention was to drop 4 SAS into Brittany on the night before D-day.  The first two groups were to set up operational centres and then receive and distribute arms to the resistance or FFI (Force Française Intérieur).  The SAS and FFI were to jointly harass the German troops in Brittany and impede them from joining the Normandy front.  In the short term there was also a possibility that the Germans would be mislead into thinking than another invasion front was being opened up in Brittany.', '*', '2003-06-21 01:15:41'),
(718, 'event', '93', 'comment', 'EN', 'The 2nd Company 3 SAS were brought back to Britain on the 22 August 1944 and were then despatched in two waves to undertake operations in the East of France.  The objective being to establish a base in the Doubs on the Suisse frontier to support the local resistance in order to slow down as much as possible the enemy retreat.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(719, 'event', '101', 'comment', 'EN', '', 'david', '2009-07-18 17:24:41'),
(720, 'event', '102', 'comment', 'EN', ' The landings in Provence occured on the 15th of August.  With a mission similar to that in Britanny, the SAS were landed in the Rhone valley to impede the retreating enemy and facilate the advance of the allied forces.  Progress was better than expected with Lyon being liberated on the 3rd of September, whereas the allies had expected this to take until the 15th November.  It was the 14th of September that the southern liberating forces met up with those coming from Normandy.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(721, 'event', '103', 'comment', 'EN', ' These missions were intended to inflict maximum losses on the retrerating enemy along the main axes north the RN6 and the RN74.  The sticks were dropped near Sarlrney, Savigny and Messey and  established bases in the Maconais.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(722, 'event', '106', 'comment', 'EN', ' A reconnaisance mission in the Compiegne region led by Lt Kirschen of the Belge SAS.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(723, 'event', '119', 'comment', 'EN', 'Arrivals in June, July 1944 etc.', '*', '2003-05-18 02:14:37'),
(724, 'event', '120', 'comment', 'EN', '&lt;p align=justify&gt;On the night of the 7/8 th June 1944 eighteen small groups from 4 SAS were parachuted into Britany to carry out specific sabotage missions.  Dropped blind without a welcoming committee they were expected to operate without contacting local residents for 48 hours while they carried out their principal mission, usually destruction of railway lines.  After this they were to remain active for 8 to 10 days with secondary missions, destruction of other communications, depots, power lines etc, as well as impeding the repair of the original target.  The groups were then to regroup on the northern or southern base Samwest or Dingson.    After the destruction of the Samwest base (12/13 June) , groups were alerted to report to Dingson.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If the invasion was abandoned, the message *les carrottes sont cuites* would alert them to make for the coast where ferries would return them to to Britain ', 'paul', '2008-03-10 00:24:28'),
(725, 'event', '128', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le stick sabote la voie ferrée entre Messac et Châteaubriant avant de rejoindre la base Dingson.', '*', '2003-06-27 09:56:01'),
(726, 'event', '129', 'comment', 'EN', '* Le stick est parachuté en Loire-Inférieure près de Saint-Gildas des Bois pour saboter la ligne de Redon à  Pontchâteau puis ils rejoignent la base Dingson.', '*', '2003-06-27 10:03:00'),
(727, 'event', '130', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le stick opère près de Rochefort-en-Terre et sabote la ligne Redon-Questembert avant de rejoindre la base Dingson', '*', '2003-06-27 09:58:08'),
(728, 'event', '131', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le stick opère vers Elven et coupe la ligne Questembert-Vannes avant de rejoindre la base Dingson', '*', '2003-06-27 09:58:26'),
(729, 'event', '132', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le groupe opère entre Ploërmel et Messac avant de rejoindre la base Dingson', '*', '2003-06-27 09:58:43'),
(730, 'event', '133', 'comment', 'EN', ' *Le stick est parachuté près de Malestroit dans le but de saboter la voie ferrée entre Ploërmel et Questembert puis les trois parachutistes rejoignent la base Dingson', '*', '2003-06-27 10:02:08'),
(731, 'event', '134', 'comment', 'EN', ' *Le stick est parachuté près de Baud pour saboter la ligne Auray-Pontivy avant de rejoindre la base Dingson', '*', '2003-06-27 10:01:08'),
(732, 'event', '135', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>*Le stick sabote la voie ferrée Saint-Méen - Ploërmel avant d\'encadrer des maquisards dans la région de Ploermel</p>', 'David Portier', '2016-01-30 10:06:45'),
(733, 'event', '136', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le stick sabote la voie ferrée entre Loudéac et Merdrignac puis encadre des maquisards dans ce secteur.', '*', '2003-06-27 10:03:43'),
(734, 'event', '137', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le stick sabote la ligne de Saint-Brieuc à  Loudéac avant de rejoindre le secteur de Gomené.', '*', '2003-06-27 10:04:13'),
(735, 'event', '138', 'comment', 'EN', '*Le groupe coupe la ligne Loudéac - Rostrenen puis opère dans la région de Corlay et participe à  la libération de Paimpol.', '*', '2003-06-27 10:04:38'),
(736, 'event', '139', 'comment', 'EN', 'Open up the route for the 3rd division US infantry by harrasing the enemy garrisions between Morlaix and Brest and impeding the reinforment of the Brest garrison from the east.  Protect the viaducs of Morlaix and Plougastel and to support the resistance.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(737, 'event', '151', 'comment', 'EN', ' Sabotage of railway lines in the South West from Nates to La Rochelle.  Harassment of the enemy, organisation of the resistance and finally holding the nothern front of the enemy pocket at La Rochelle.   ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(738, 'event', '160', 'comment', 'FR', '<p align=justify>Depuis près d\'un an, le Lt Marienne entraîne ses hommes pour ce moment tant attendu de pouvoir, le premier, fouler le sol de France en libérateur.\r\n<br>Il est 00h30 le 6 juin 1944 et à  travers le trou du Stirling, le dispatcher regarde défiler la campagne bretonne. La lumière est au rouge, \"Action - Station\".\r\n<br>Les hommes du stick Marienne se lèvent et accrochent la sangle de leur parachute à  la static line qui traverse l\'avion.\r\n<br>Soudain, le pilote découvre les repères et la proximité de la DZ. La lumière passe au vert. \"Go!\"', 'David Portier', '2006-10-16 12:35:48'),
(739, 'event', '330', 'comment', 'FR', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Le groupe du lieutenant Marienne touche terre à 00h45 à  deux kilomètres de l\'endroit prévu, dans les landes à  l\'est du hameau de Halliguen.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Sans le savoir, les parachutistes français sont tombés à  huit cents mètres du Moulin de la Grée à  Plumelec, transformé en poste d\'observation par les Allemands.<br />Aussitôt, l\'alerte est donnée et un détachement de Géorgiens se lance à  la recherche des SAS. <br /><br />Tandis qu\'une partie du stick est à  la recherche de la malle en osier du capitaine André Hunter-Hue alias Fernand, agent du SOE parachuté avec les SAS, le caporal Bouétard et l\'équipe radio sont encerclés. Rapidement, Emile Bouétard est blessé et achevé par l\'ennemi alors que Jordan, Etrich et Sauvé sont faits prisonniers.<br /><br />Au bruit des combats, le stick se disperse. Tandis que le lieutenant Marienne, Louis et Krysik décrochent vers le sud, traversent La Claie et rejoignent la Petite-Métairie, le Sgt/C Raufast et le capitaine André partent vers Saint-Jean-Brévelay.</p>', 'David Portier', '2012-10-13 11:14:18'),
(740, 'event', '162', 'comment', 'EN', ' A standard 2nd SAS mission dropped to the SE of Vtre to collect information on enmey movements and to harrass them.', 'David Portier', '2006-05-22 11:51:11'),
(741, 'event', '163', 'comment', 'EN', ' The stick, led by Captain Lee 2SAS was parachuted to the South of Paris in July with the objective of capturing Rommel.', 'David Portier', '2006-03-17 14:49:53'),
(742, 'event', '164', 'comment', 'EN', '<p align=justify>Deplante was charged by Bourgoin to set up a northern base to replace the lost Samwest base.  The was to receive redistribute and then co-ordinate the work of SAS and resistance coming from the overrun Dingson base and the Duault(Samwest) bases.', 'David Portier', '2006-09-14 14:08:34'),
(743, 'event', '165', 'comment', 'EN', 'As the liberating forces gained a substantial foothold in Normandy and the enemy forces in Britany were being defeated, the SAS were being required to operate further east.  To supply adequate transport a major delivery of jeeps was made, by parachute and by gliders under the noses of the occupation forces in Vannes.  Betbeze. Paoli, Itturia and the reserve 4SAS arrived with the jeeps near Mallachappe.  There was a certain impatiance in these forces having missed the first two months of the liberation, however the enemy were far from defeated and much of France was still occupied so there was still work to be done. ', 'david', '2009-06-16 18:24:21'),
(744, 'event', '166', 'comment', 'EN', ' Harassing the enemy facilitating the progress of alied forces arriving from the south. ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(745, 'event', '167', 'comment', 'EN', ' Paracuted South of Lamure on 18/8/1944', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(746, 'event', '168', 'comment', 'EN', '', 'David Portier', '2012-05-18 13:54:48');
INSERT INTO `text` (`id`, `objecttype`, `objid`, `attribute`, `language`, `comment`, `contributor`, `update_dt`) VALUES
(747, 'event', '168', 'comment', 'FR', '<p>Le stick du sous-lieutenant Gayard est parachuté dans la nuit du 14 au 15  août sur le terrain \"Heliotrope\" situé au col de Casse-Froide à six kilomètres au  sud-est de Beaujeu.</p>', 'David Portier', '2012-06-25 19:41:03'),
(748, 'event', '169', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>During the  night of 14 to 15 August  Aspirant Barres and his stick were parachuted into a field situated by the col Casse-Froide six kilometres south east of Beaujeu.</p>', 'paul golder', '2012-09-19 03:02:17'),
(749, 'event', '169', 'comment', 'FR', '<p>Le stick de l\'aspirant Barres est parachuté dans la nuit du 14 au 15  août sur un terrain situé au col de Casse-Froide à six kilomètres au  sud-est de Beaujeu.</p>', 'David Portier', '2012-05-18 13:54:12'),
(750, 'event', '170', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>Après un premier voyage dans la nuit du 14 août, le stick du sous-lieutenant Ferchaud est parachuté dans la nuit du 16 au 17 août sur le terrain \"Vinaigrette\" sur la commune de Larajasse, entre Saint-Symphorien et Sainte-Catherine.</p>\r\n<p>Dans la nuit du 18 août, le stick et un groupe de maquisards sabotent la voie ferrée au niveau de la garde de l\'Arbresle. La station de pompage est également détruite ainsi qu\'un important matériel.</p>\r\n<p>Le 22 août, le S/Lt Ferchaud et ses hommes attaquent un dépôt de carburant à Pierre-Bénite.</p>\r\n<p>Le stick est particulièrement actif et monte de nombreuses embuscades entre Roanne et Lyon.</p>\r\n<p>Le 3 septembre, les SAS font leur entrée dans Lyon et participent au nettoyage de la ville. Le 12 septembre, le S/Lt Ferchaud se voit remettre une décoration par le général de Lattre.</p>', 'David Portier', '2019-04-20 15:58:12'),
(751, 'event', '171', 'comment', 'EN', ' Dropped near Saint Martin la Plaine nord de Rive de Gier', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(752, 'event', '172', 'comment', 'EN', '', 'David Portier', '2012-05-18 13:21:43'),
(753, 'event', '173', 'comment', 'EN', 'As the situation in Brittany became complex a reconnaissance mission was dispatched to contact Bourgoin and Déplante and to ensure an officer returned to England to report back.  Major Cary-Elwes supported by a small team of parachutists was sent to make contact and captain Leblond reported back.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(754, 'event', '177', 'comment', 'EN', ' In these two zones the enemy were remaining in their garisons and did not present particularly conventint targets for SAS action.  There was also no major objective to impede movement nor the arrival of reinforcements.  The two missions supported by resistance  attacked garrisons at Egleton (Snelgrove) and Bourganeuf (Marshall).  The 24 th August they regrouped and turned thier attention to the retreating enemy forces at Charteauroux.  Operating from the forest of Chataueroux supported by resistance and aviation they harrased the retreating enemy who surrenderd  at Issoudoun on the 10th September.  The 14th September the two missions joined operation Moses at the enemy pocket of Saint Nazaire.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(755, 'event', '178', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>*</p>', 'paul golder', '2013-12-18 17:06:25'),
(756, 'event', '179', 'comment', 'EN', ' dropped 2/8/1944', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(757, 'event', '180', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>11 men took off from Tempsford in two Hudson and landed at bonbon 7/8/1944</p>', 'David P', '2019-10-25 18:57:39'),
(758, 'event', '181', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>14 men of the 3rd squadron / 3rd SAS</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In the night of 7 to 8 of august, The sticks of aspirants Marc Marchal and Roger Decours were dropped near Magnac-Laval.</p>', 'David P', '2019-10-25 19:02:18'),
(759, 'event', '182', 'comment', 'EN', ' landed at Bonbon 9/8/1944', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(760, 'event', '183', 'comment', 'EN', ' dropped 14/8/44', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(761, 'event', '184', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>The group was landed by Dakota on the dropping zone \"Bonbon\" in the night of  27 to 28 August. The SAS carried out several strikes towards the the forest of Mareuil and Chauvigny.  At the beginning of September aspirant Levi and his men met up with lieutenant Leblond (Samson) at Le Blanc. The detachment operated in the direction of Chateauroux, La Chatre and then Limoges before rejoining the pocket of Saint-Nazaire.</p>', 'paul golder', '2011-01-31 09:58:55'),
(762, 'event', '185', 'comment', 'EN', ' Overland reinforcement of the Dickens, Moses and Harrod missions', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(763, 'event', '210', 'comment', 'EN', ' Led by Lt Rousseau of 2SAS this sabotage mission operated in the Vosges.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(764, 'event', '211', 'comment', 'EN', ' Members of 3 and 4 SAS also participated in actions with 1 & 2 SAS and with sticks from the Belgium SAS (5SAS).  Often this was to provide support with local knowledge or of course language skills.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(765, 'event', '213', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>Bourgoin was asked to provide a detachment of troups to escort Intelligence officers into Paris as it was being liberated.  Apart from protection they were required to help liberate Gestapo prisons and to help in the arrest of collaborators and spies.  Beteze was assigned the task and took a number of jeeps and about 20 men with him.  They thus had the honour of arriving with the liberating forces and parading down the Champs Elysees.  Itturia and his jeep were assigned to the detachment but were ambushed immediately before setting out from Vannes</p>', 'paul golder', '2013-12-10 09:55:41'),
(766, 'event', '214', 'comment', 'EN', ' A sabotage 2nd mission, commanded by Captain Scott, against communication routes between the Moselle and Rhin.  Lt Grumbach particiapated in one of the eight sticks dropped. ', 'David Portier', '2006-05-22 11:51:59'),
(767, 'event', '215', 'comment', 'EN', 'Teams of radio operators were dropped near Pesquen as reinforcements for those in the field.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(768, 'event', '216', 'comment', 'EN', ' To impede the retreat of the enemy by destroying railway connections and bridges and harrassing the enemy along their route. After 14th September they continued supporting the mission Dickens in Loire Altlantic and then at La Rochelle.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(769, 'event', '220', 'comment', 'FR', 'Tout se déroule bien pour les équipes Pierre 3 et Pierre 4 qui sont parachutées à  l\'endroit prévu, près de Locarn à  deux ou trois kilomètres de la forêt de Duault. <br /><br />Les hommes se regroupent rapidement puis prennent un peu de repos dans les fourrés le temps que les deux officiers, les lieutenant Botella et Deschamps, fassent le point. Quelques minutes plus tard, ils se mettent en route vers la lisière des bois de Duault. Après environ une heure de marche, au lever du jour le matin du 6 juin, les SAS installent leur campement et André Botella prend contact par radio avec le Quartier Général à  Londres.<br /><br />Au matin, le groupe entre en contact avec deux patriotes membres de la compagnie FTP \" Tito \" de Maël-Pestivien. Aussitôt, les deux maquisards partent prévenir l\'Etat-major FFI des Côtes-du-Nord qui est rassemblé à  Peumerit-Quintin. <br />Peu à  peu, les résistants affluent à  la base Samwest. Les parachutistes préparent alors une dropping-zone pour accueillir les renforts et ils demandent des parachutages d\'armes et de matériel.<br />', 'david', '2009-01-21 18:39:44'),
(770, 'event', '120', 'comment', 'FR', '<p>Mission du 4th SAS</p>\r\n<p>Effectifs engagés: 56 hommes</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dans la nuit du 7 au 8 juin, dix-huit petites équipes de sabotage de 3 à  5 hommes sont larguées à  travers l\'ensemble de la Bretagne afin de réaliser des actions de sabotage bien définies, principalement contre les moyens de communication de l\'ennemi.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ces équipes sont larguées \"blind\", c\'est à  dire sans comité de réception, et elles ont reçu l\'ordre de ne pas prendre contact avec la population civile. Chaque groupe doit effectuer une mission principale qui est jugée prioritaire et qui consiste généralement à  saboter la voie ferrée Brest-Paris. Les SAS doivent réaliser ensuite différentes missions secondaires (couper les lignes souterraines et les lignes téléphoniques, abattre les pylônes à  haute tension) pour créer le maximum de chaos dans les lignes ennemies et empêcher que les unités allemandes stationnées en Bretagne ne rejoignent la Normandie.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Les différentes équipes ont dix jours pour opérer dans le secteur qui leur a été attribué puis elles doivent ensuite rejoindre les bases Dingson ou Samwest afin de prendre un peu de repos et se réarmer.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">A la suite de la dispersion de la base Samwest, les équipes reçoivent par radio l\'ordre de rejoindre la base sud. En fait, plusieurs groupes restent alors dans leur secteur où ils encadrent des patriotes et poursuivent les actions de sabotage.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Depuis l\'aérodrome de Brize-Norton, les bombardiers Armstrong Whitworth AW.41 \"Albemarle\" des 295th, 296th, 297th et 570th Squadron du 38th Group transportent chacun deux Parties vers leur zone d\'opération.</p>\r\n<p> </p>', 'David Portier', '2012-12-06 19:50:57'),
(771, 'event', '225', 'comment', 'EN', 'Squadron 1 arrived at Briare on the 30st August and immediately made contact with the enemy.  Captain Larralde requested reinforcements and  the 3rd company arrived however counter attacks by Varnier and Lesecq had already remedied the situation.  Squadron 1 reamined in the region of Briare eliminating the enemy in the area and helping in the liberation of Bourges.', '*', '2003-05-06 08:58:23'),
(772, 'event', '226', 'comment', 'EN', 'The second squadron was sent to patrol the left bank of the Loire in the direction of Nevers.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(773, 'event', '227', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>The third squadron of captain Puech-Samson arrived on the Loire the 31 August ans established itself in the region of Gien.</p>\r\n<p>Patrols operated towards Châteauroux, Isoudun  and Vierzon.  A large convoy was attacked on the 6th September near Neuvy-Pailloux.  At Mareuil, the patrols of aspirant Fauquet and S/Lt Nicol attacked and destroyed vehicles carrying the German headquarters staff of Bairritz.</p>\r\n<p>The following days the 3rd  squadron made an impressive penetration into the enemy held territory, in the south east direction of Angoulême, Saints Cognac and eventually Périgueux and Bordeaux where the jeeps regrouped on the 13 September.</p>', 'paul golder', '2012-09-19 02:58:12'),
(774, 'event', '228', 'comment', 'EN', 'Direction Nevers<br />', 'david', '2008-03-13 18:26:30'),
(775, 'event', '228', 'comment', 'FR', '<p>Ce squadron vient d\'être formé à Vannes par le capitaine Déplante et regroupe en grande partie de nombreux jeunes maquisards bretons. </p><p>Les premiers éléments du 4e squadron atteignent Briare le 5 septembre et patrouillent dans le secteur de Nevers. </p><p>De retour de Paris, le lieutenant Betbèze et ses hommes sont chargés le 10 septembre de prendre contact à Autun avec les éléments de reconnaissance de la 1re Armée française du général de Lattre. Dans le même temps, les sous-lieutenants de Camaret et Cochin et les éléments du 4e squadron poursuivent les opérations de harcèlement entre Saint-Amand, Sancoins, Saint-Pierre-le-Moutiers et Decize.</p><p><br></p><p>Dans la soirée du 11 septembre, les jeeps du capitaine Déplante tournent autour du village de Saint-Pierre-le-Moutiers afin de prêter main forte au peloton Le Bobinnec du 2e squadron. Les parachutistes font croire à un important détachement de reconnaissance allié. Après négociation, le capitaine Déplante obtient la reddition de près de 2.500 soldats allemands qui sont alors dirigés vers Moulins et Nevers.</p>', 'David P', '2020-01-07 08:32:12'),
(776, 'event', '229', 'comment', 'EN', 'A reconnaissance mission by Lt Gabaudan on the 26th August reported that the enemy were well, established in the region around Pouiily sur Loire.  On the 29th August Bourgoin sent three companies to Briare where they were to establish a base.  A fourth company which had just been created was to follow as a headquaters company which had first to repair the remaining vehicles.\r\n\r\nThe enemy forces appeared to be guarding the bridges essential for any retreat from the south west to the north east.\r\n\r\nThe objective was to provide a mobile unit harrasing the enemy retreating from the South West to the North East of France. \r\n\r\n(the reports do not enable a complete distribution of men across the four Squadrons.)\r\n\r\nThus 54 jeeps each with 4 SAS together with a number of trailers and lorries left Vannes and set of  for the Loire.  This comprised all 4 SAS and some resistants who had joined them.  Betbeze led the 4SAS to Briare where the HQ was established.\r\n\r\n A total of 38 officers and 279 men were involved', '*', '2003-05-06 08:56:21'),
(777, 'event', '230', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>Après être parvenu à échapper à l\'encerclement de Falaise, les unités allemandes tentent de franchir la Seine.</p>\r\n<p>Différents éléments de la Brigade SAS reçoivent pour mission d\'effectuer des missions de sabotage, harcèlement et renseignement en Normandie dans le secteur d\'Elbeuf.</p>\r\n<p>Ainsi, la mission est confiée à 5 hommes du 1st SAS - 39 hommes du 2nd SAS - 57 hommes de la Belgian Ind Coy qui sont parachutés les nuits des 16 et 17 août dans des conditions difficiles et souvent dans des zones éloignées des DZ prévues.</p>\r\n<p>Dans la nuit du 16 au 17 août, un stick composé de 5 hommes du 1st SAS aux ordres du Cpl/C Chapell et 5 hommes de la Compagnie Belge aux ordres du Sgt M. de Vulder sont parachutés à Saint-Just. (Mission Trueform 1 / Ortie)</p>\r\n<p>Dans le même temps, un stick de 10 hommes de la Belgian Ind Coy aux ordres du Lt Heilporn (alias Davies) et du Sgt Sgt H. Verschuere est parachuté près de Saint-André/Eure (Mission Trueform 1 / Kioskue)</p>\r\n<p>Enfin, un stick de 11 hommes du 2nd SAS aux ordres du Lt Holland et comprenant notamment Eugène Bosson, est parachuté à St-Paul de Fourques. (Trueform 1 / St-Paul)</p>\r\n<p>Dans la nuit du 17 au 18 août, ce sont cinq sticks aux ordres du Captain Baillie (Trueform 2E - 11 hommes), du Lt Samarine (Trueform 2F - 11 hommes), du Cpt Dulait (alias Dill) (Trueform 2M - 16 hommes), des Sgts Pus et de Rechter (Trueform 2H - 16 hommes) et du Cpt Delelienne (alias Dulaing) (Trueform 2G - 17 hommes) qui sont parachutés en Normandie.</p>', 'David Portier', '2019-05-26 12:38:07'),
(778, 'person', '674', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>Born in Demangevelle (70<br /> on 22 May 1917.</p>', 'Administrator', '2017-04-30 16:35:09'),
(779, 'event', '270', 'comment', 'EN', ' Complete records of the disposition of all Frankilin members are not available so those non allocated are listed here.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(780, 'event', '271', 'comment', 'EN', 'As the autumn turned to winter, the Germans were fighting a slow rearguard action and the war in Europe was still not settled.  A surprised awaited the Americans in the Ardennes as on the 16th December the Germans under Von Rundstedt made a major offensive.<br /><br />The allies decided to commit the French SAS to the support of the Americans.  They were near by at Montmirail and entry by air was impossible so an overland insertion was required.  4SAS  had 40 jeeps resulting from the Spencer operations on the Loire.  The squadron, left Montmirail on the 24 December for Bertrix and St Hubert in the Belgian Ardennes.     <br />The weather was foul and the SAS held their position in the front for a month until 25th January 1945.  On the 25th the SAS were recalled to Bertrix, their base for the operations in the Ardennes.  The 29th saw them back in Montmirail and by the end of the month they were in Bases in East Anglia awaiting further action.', 'david', '2008-03-13 19:39:35'),
(781, 'event', '272', 'comment', 'EN', ' It was only 9 days after returning from the Ardennes that the SAS were on the move again.  Starting the 9th of February they transferred From their base in Montmirail to Le Havre and by the 17th they were bound for England.\r\nThe allies standard technique for driving forward against the enemy was to lay down a heavy artillery and air bombardment prior to the arrival of the allied tanks.  However Queen Wilhelmine had requested that the allies should make an effort to spare the dykes and drainage systems.  Thus Calvert, commander of the SAS, proposed that the French battalions should be used to precede the Canadians advancing to Groningen.  They were to seize some bridges and destroy others thus enabling the rapid advance of the Canadians.\r\n\r\nThe plan was to drop 23 sticks of 2RCP and 24 sticks of 3RCP from Stirlings together with 18 jeeps from Halifaxs.   The intention was to drop them on the 6-7th April and they were to either meet at the airport of Steenwijk if the allies had arrived or else regroup at Coeverden.  The Canadians should arrive within 72 hours.  The SAS were required to return ASAP to England with a view to future missions.\r\n\r\nThe operation was not low key, with announcements by radio, a supporting airforce action and the dropping of a number of dummies all to give the illusion of a larger operation.\r\n\r\nThe operation was eventually scheduled for the night of the 7-8 April.  It was not until 17th of April that the last men flew back to Britain, the operation intended to last 3 days lasted 10.\r\n', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(782, 'event', '273', 'comment', 'EN', 'The French SAS received parachute training during 1942-1943 from the Polish airforce at Largo in Scotland.  The lists of parachutes brevete includes non SAS Free French.', '*', '2003-03-27 09:05:43'),
(783, 'event', '293', 'comment', 'EN', 'The French CIA arrived in North Africa in Janary 1942 and were to support the liberation of North Africa fighting alomgside the Britich SAS until January 1943.', '*', '2003-04-10 04:52:11'),
(784, 'event', '294', 'comment', 'EN', ' Operating in Libya behind the Axis front at El Alamein, the objectives were to destroy enemy planes on the ground, harrasing enemy convoys and destroying lines of communications.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(785, 'event', '299', 'comment', 'EN', 'A French SAS team, accompanied by Lord Jellico (BR) and Lt Petrakis (Greek). was tranfered by submarine leaving Alexandria on the 7 th June 1942.   The objective of the mission was to attack the airfield of Heraklion, to sabotage planes, installations, munitions and fuel.    \r\n\r\nHaving achieved the sabotage the SAS were found by the enemy.  Leostic was killed the other French SAS captured..  Thery were transfered to prison camps in Germany. ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(786, 'event', '300', 'comment', 'EN', 'Operation Snowdrop was launched to gain control of the port of Benghasi and destroy enemy shipping in the port. Leaving Kabrit on 15th August 1942 the SAS esatblished a base at Koufra from which an attach on Benghasi was launched. The LRDG was simultaneaously attaking Barce and Tobruk. The force was detected and came under air attack. The mission was aborted, many SAS wounded and killed, much equipment destroyed.\r\n', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(787, 'event', '302', 'comment', 'EN', '<p>This mission was betrayed and all participants captured except Jordan. Many of the prisoners were to die when the boat, the Nino Bixio which was transfering them to Italy, was sunk.</p>', 'David Portier', '2018-06-26 10:49:20'),
(788, 'event', '307', 'comment', 'EN', 'On the 8th November the Allies, American and British, launched an invasion from the west with landings in Algeria and Marocco. Rommel\'s days in North Africa were numbered, however he was under orders to resist at all cost.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(789, 'event', '308', 'comment', 'EN', ' On arrival in Egypt the Company was sent to  Kabrit on the Suez canal where the British SAS Brigade under Stirling had their base.  Over the next year many voluntiers were to arrive at Kabrit from various parts of the French Empire.  ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(790, 'event', '309', 'comment', 'EN', ' The operation was to  attack the road and rail links between Aghelia and Tripoli.  The operation was carried out with mainly new troups and resulted in heavy losses to B Squadron. We do not have details of the French Squadron complement to B Squadrons actions apart from it being led by Lt Martin so all remaining FF have been allocated here.  ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(791, 'event', '310', 'comment', 'EN', ' The aim of the mission was to impede enemy airfields from attacking supply convoys trying to reach Malta.  Seven airfields behind the enemy front at Tobruk were to be targeted by the SAS supported by the LRDG at the same time a group would attack the enemy base of Herakilion on the island of Crete.  This SAS group was to be carried to Crete by submarine from Alexandria. ', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(792, 'event', '312', 'comment', 'EN', '*', '*', '2003-05-16 04:29:22'),
(793, 'event', '312', 'comment', 'FR', '<p>Suite à&nbsp;la demande du général de Gaulle, il est décidé que les parachutistes français doivent être rassemblés en Grande-Bretagne afin de se préparer pour les opérations de Libération en Europe.</p><p><br></p><p>Le 16 décembre 1942, une vingtaine d\'hommes de la 1re CCP embarque à&nbsp;Suez sous le commandement du capitaine Christian Fouchet, assisté des S/Lts Mairet et Jacquier. Le capitaine Jean Lambert, hospitalisé au Caire, doit rejoindre plus tard.</p><p>Le convoi atteint Durban le 31 décembre et repart le 25 janvier. La 1re CCP débarque à Cape Town le 29 janvier et fait escale pendant deux mois. Les hommes embarquent alors le 9 avril 1943 et débarquent à Greenock le 25 avril. Les parachutistes sont de retour à Camberley.</p>', 'David P', '2019-09-27 10:31:15'),
(794, 'event', '315', 'comment', 'EN', ' A small group led by Jordan and Martin remained to see the completion of the war in North Africa.  The Battalion members who remained in North Africa continued their sabotage and harrasment of the enemy comunication lines from Sousse to Gabes.\r\n\r\nFour French patrols were operating together with patrols form the British SAS  Three patrols led by Jordan were to operate on the east of the Tunisia coast.  The fourth patrol led by Martin under Striling was to reach ourt westwards towards the approaching American 1st army.  The result was rather bad for the SAS with 15 of th 40 men being captured, including Stirling and Jordan.\r\n\r\nThose not captured were eventually reunited in Constantine 7/2/1943 ', '*', '2003-05-16 04:33:59'),
(795, 'event', '316', 'comment', 'EN', ' The patrol arrived at Constantine 7/2/1943.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(796, 'event', '317', 'comment', 'EN', ' The Jordan patrol was captured on the 28/1/1943 at Djedel Bou-Hadma. ', '*', '2003-05-19 07:29:50'),
(797, 'event', '318', 'comment', 'EN', 'The patrol had two jeeps made contact with the 1st US army 30/1/1943 at the Djebel Orbata', '*', '2003-05-19 07:31:09'),
(798, 'event', '319', 'comment', 'EN', 'Having lost both their jeeps the patrol finished the mission on foot arriving at Zennouch station on 30/1/1943 to be met by the 1st US army.', '*', '2003-01-01 00:00:00'),
(799, 'event', '121', 'comment', 'FR', '<p>Parachuté près de Plouagat, le groupe sabote la voie ferrée Saint-Brieuc - Guingamp près de Châtelaudren. Suite au déraillement d\'un train, la ligne est rendue inutilisable.</p>\r\n<p>La Party 401 prend alors contact avec la résistance et s\'installe près de Saint-Fiacre. Fin, juin, les trois hommes retrouvent le SAS René Siccardi, rescapé de la base Samwest, et ensemble, ils rejoignent le secteur de Loudéac puis de Merdrignac.</p>\r\n<p>Début août, les hommes participent au combat pour la libération de Merdrignac et la région.</p>', 'David Portier', '2012-10-21 17:12:28'),
(800, 'event', '340', 'comment', 'EN', ' Jedburgh Frederick was assigned to the Duault base and later worked with Smith (Wash) and Deplante (Grog) near Peumerit-Quintin.', 'David Portier', '2005-10-15 06:25:13'),
(801, 'event', '343', 'comment', 'EN', 'Fin juillet, un premier détachement précurseur composé de l\'équipe Jedburgh Ronald et de quelques S.A.S. français dont André Soupé, est parachuté près de Kerien. Ces hommes doivent armer et encadrer les maquisards mais également préparer la réception de l\'Etat-major FFI. <br />Dans la nuit du 4 août, le colonel Eon et son Etat-major sont largués en compagnie du colonel Passy et de divers éléments du BCRA et de l\'Intelligence Service. Ils sont accompagnés également par quelques parachutistes SAS dont le major Cary-Elwes et l\'équipe radio dirigée par le Sgt Delplanque.<br />', 'david', '2009-01-17 20:55:42'),
